The '''Hearst Expedition''' was an archaeological project led by the [[University of California]] to explore burial grounds at and around [[Qift]], [[Egypt]]. The expedition spanned the years 1899-1905, and was named for Phoebe Hearst, mother of [[William Randolph Hearst]], the newspaper magnate who funded it.<ref>{{cite book|title=Ancient Egyptian Medicine|first=John F.|last=Nunn|page=35|year=2002|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press}}</ref> [[George A. Reisner]] directed the expedition, and is credited with some of its most important finds, including the [[stela]] of Prince [[Wepemnofret]] and the [[Hearst Medical Papyrus]].

