[[File:Hand Constantine Musei Capitolini MC786.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Hand of the [[Colossus of Constantine]]]]
'''''The Artist's Despair Before the Grandeur of Ancient Ruins''''' ([[German language|German]]: ''Der Künstler verzweifelnd vor der Grösse der antiken Trümmer'') is a [[drawing]] in red [[chalk]] with brown [[Wash (painting)|wash]] executed between 1778-1780 by [[Johann Heinrich Füssli]]. It depicts an artist's response to [[ruins]], namely those of the [[Colossus of Constantine]] at the [[Capitoline Museums]] in [[Rome]]. The work was acquired by the [[Kunsthaus Zürich]] in 1940.<ref name="Zurich">{{cite web |url=http://www.kunsthaus.ch/en/the-collection/prints-and-drawings/johann-heinrich-fuseli/?redirect_url=title%3DRГ©gleme |title=Johann Heinrich Fuseli |publisher=[[Kunsthaus Zürich]] |accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref>

The artist's despair may be caused by "the impossibility of emulating the greatness of the past", by the knowledge that all things must decay, or by a sense of unfulfilled longing and dislocation.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VEEot7jUvS8C&pg=PA15#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Writing Rome: Textual Approaches to the City |author=Edwards, Catharine |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |year=1996 |isbn=978-0-521-55952-2 |page=15}}</ref> Distortions of [[Perspective (graphical)|perspective]] and the "plunge into the abyss" along the right edge conjure up a sense of [[nightmare]].<ref name="Zurich"/> [[SPQR]] may be read in the [[Epigraphy|inscription]] on the base of the foot, while vegetation sprouts up near the hand; the artist, in a "fit of [[Depression (mood)|melancholy]]", is dwarfed by the fragments of the past.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Built, the Unbuilt and the Unbuildable: In Pursuit of Architectural Meaning |author=Harbison, Robert |publisher=[[MIT Press]] |year=1991 |isbn=0-262-08204-7 |pages=108f}}</ref>

